library-narrow.png
settings-narrow.png
shell-now.png
klog-filtered.png
debug-*.png
ui-debug-*.png

# ─── Local /tmp helpers + diagnostic scripts ─────────────────────────────
# Ad-hoc Python scripts written during debugging sessions
# (sendpayload, test_shell, klog_monitor, …) — they live in /tmp
# during dev and shouldn't get committed if copied into the repo root.
sendpayload.py
test_shell.py
test_screens.py
klog_monitor.py
klog_now.txt
klog_phase*.txt
ps5_startup.log
ps5upload_*.log
ps5upload_main_entered

# ─── macOS Application Support cache (extracted payload at runtime) ─────
# In case anyone runs the bundle from inside this checkout.
ps5upload.elf.tmp
ps5upload.elf.tmp.*
ps5upload.elf.gz.blake3.tmp

# ─── Built payload artifacts ────────────────────────────────────────────
# CI rebuilds these from C source on every release (see
# .github/workflows/release.yml: "make payload" step). Tracking them
# caused two recurring problems:
#   1. Binary churn: contributors who run `make payload` locally get a
#      diff-noise commit they have to revert (hit twice in 2.8.0 dev).
#   2. Stale-payload risk: a contributor changing payload C source
#      could commit without rebuilding, shipping a desktop build that
#      embeds the OLD .elf while CI release ships the NEW one.
# The desktop build script (client/src-tauri/build.rs::require_file)
# errors with "Build it first: make -C payload all" when missing, so
# the dev experience for fresh clones is still clean.
payload/ps5upload.elf
payload/ps5upload.elf.gz

# ─── Personal scratch + notes ───────────────────────────────────────────
# Anything in /scratch or /notes-local that a dev wants to keep
# locally without checking in.
/scratch/
/notes-local/
NOTES.local.md
TODO.local.md

# Tauri mobile generated projects (regenerate with: tauri android init / ios init)
client/src-tauri/gen/

# Locally-built/signed Android artifacts (release flow produces these)
PS5Upload-android.apk
PS5Upload-android.apk.idsig
*.idsig

# NEVER commit signing material. The Android release keystore + passwords
# live in GitHub Actions secrets (ANDROID_KEYSTORE_BASE64 etc.) and an
# off-repo backup (password manager). Committing a keystore to this PUBLIC
# repo would expose the app's signing identity — anyone could push a
# malicious "update" your users' devices would trust. This is a guard so a
# keystore can't be added by accident.
*.jks
*.keystore
*.p12
*.pepk
*.pfx
key.properties
